This use is not different in kind from the use of unus with superlatives and words denoting emi- nence, where it seems to have an intensive force, as in ii 26, 64 ‘unam omnium rem pulcherrimam'; ii 18, 43 ‘ quae una ce- teris excellebat’; nor is it different from its use in passages where it seems to have a disparaging force, as in Catullus 22, 8 ‘unus caprimulgus.' For a unit among goat-herds is a humble unit, while a unit among superlatives is an exalted unit, and (as in our passage and in Or. i 29, 132 ⁴ unus paterfamilias’) a unit among a multitude is an ordinary unit.
